  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Understanding customer financial activities\n- Assessing risk levels of customers\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Monitoring transaction patterns\n- Identifying potential suspicious activities\n\n4. Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Training staff on detection and reporting\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n5. Legal Frameworks\n- Complying with laws like the Bank Secrecy Act\n- Following international anti-money laundering standards\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\n6. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal liability\n- Loss of operating licenses\n\nThese obligations aim to prevent criminal financial activities and maintain financial system integrity.",
